00:00:30.500 --> 00:00:32.700
PROFESSOR JOHN GABRIELI:
Good afternoon.

00:00:37.030 --> 00:00:40.490
So last time we talked about
neuropsychiatric disorder.

00:00:40.490 --> 00:00:42.720
And I just want to remind you
that we talked about it in a

00:00:42.720 --> 00:00:44.880
couple of context
of challenges.

00:00:44.880 --> 00:00:48.500
That historically, different
cultures at different times

00:00:48.500 --> 00:00:50.870
have interpreted unusual
behavior in

00:00:50.870 --> 00:00:52.470
very different ways.

00:00:52.470 --> 00:00:56.310
From trephination, where you
have to release evil spirits,

00:00:56.310 --> 00:01:02.370
to possession, to what we would
now consider brutal

00:01:02.370 --> 00:01:05.430
patterns of taking
people away from

00:01:05.430 --> 00:01:07.740
society who behave unusually.

00:01:07.740 --> 00:01:11.230
And that even in recent times,
things like in the Soviet

00:01:11.230 --> 00:01:14.720
Union, the diagnosis of people
who protest at utilitarian

00:01:14.720 --> 00:01:18.410
governments is a socially
defined diagnosis.

00:01:18.410 --> 00:01:21.530
Obviously things like definition
of homosexuality is

00:01:21.530 --> 00:01:24.200
a psychiatric disorder until
about 20 years ago.

00:01:24.200 --> 00:01:26.160
It was a socially defined
disorder.

00:01:26.160 --> 00:01:27.630
So there's a lot
of challenges.

00:01:27.630 --> 00:01:30.150
On the other hand, there's a lot
of people suffering with a

00:01:30.150 --> 00:01:33.430
huge range of neuropsychiatric
disorders.

00:01:33.430 --> 00:01:36.110
So we're going to talk some
more about that today.

00:01:36.110 --> 00:01:40.890
Think a little bit more about
issues of treatment, talk a

00:01:40.890 --> 00:01:43.840
bit about depression,
and ADHD.

00:01:43.840 --> 00:01:46.260
And I think of depression and
ADHD, attention deficit

00:01:46.260 --> 00:01:51.360
hyperactivity disorder, as
kind of different as

00:01:51.360 --> 00:01:52.110
schizophrenia.

00:01:52.110 --> 00:01:55.860
So most of us, except for the
1% approximately who have

00:01:55.860 --> 00:01:59.030
schizophrenia, don't
hear voices, right.

00:01:59.030 --> 00:02:00.750
That's an unusual thing.

00:02:00.750 --> 00:02:03.920
But all of us can be sad.

00:02:03.920 --> 00:02:07.080
And many children are what we
would consider to be a bit

00:02:07.080 --> 00:02:11.200
hyperactive, compared to a
teenager or an adult, right.

00:02:11.200 --> 00:02:14.160
They won't sit still quietly in
a large classroom like this

00:02:14.160 --> 00:02:15.370
for very long.

00:02:15.370 --> 00:02:17.580
And so when we talk about
disorders like these.

00:02:17.580 --> 00:02:20.686
These are in some ways
exaggerations, or extensions,

00:02:20.686 --> 00:02:23.460
of what we consider typical
everyday behavior.

00:02:23.460 --> 00:02:26.580
But moving into a realm that
makes life difficult for those

00:02:26.580 --> 00:02:28.620
who get the diagnosis.

00:02:28.620 --> 00:02:31.100
So when it comes to treatment,
there's sort of two giant

00:02:31.100 --> 00:02:32.170
classes of them.

00:02:32.170 --> 00:02:33.700
One of them is behavioral
treatment.

00:02:33.700 --> 00:02:36.550
Broadly speaking, you could
call them talk therapies.

00:02:36.550 --> 00:02:40.240
And the other one is medical
treatment with drugs.

00:02:40.240 --> 00:02:44.650
Within psychotherapy, which
really covers all of the talk

00:02:44.650 --> 00:02:47.230
therapies, people sometimes
make a distinction between

00:02:47.230 --> 00:02:50.935
psychoanalysis and cognitive
behavioral therapy, or CBT.

00:02:53.470 --> 00:02:55.140
So what is psychological
therapy?

00:02:55.140 --> 00:02:58.910
So you might have a sense that
there's a lot of organization,

00:02:58.910 --> 00:03:01.030
and rules, and regulations
about this.

00:03:01.030 --> 00:03:04.040
But the truth of the matter is
that psychotherapy is a social

00:03:04.040 --> 00:03:05.960
interaction in which a trained
professional tries to help

00:03:05.960 --> 00:03:07.890
another person behave and
feel differently.

00:03:07.890 --> 00:03:09.920
There's really no boundaries
on that.

00:03:09.920 --> 00:03:10.160
OK.

00:03:10.160 --> 00:03:11.530
There's no official rules.

00:03:11.530 --> 00:03:14.020
There's more and less official
channels we're used to.

00:03:14.020 --> 00:03:16.000
But it can be a very wide
sources of this.

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:17.470
And if you flip open--

00:03:17.470 --> 00:03:19.450
this is an archaic thing--
yellow pages.

00:03:19.450 --> 00:03:22.460
I realize a few years ago
people, yellow pages.

00:03:22.460 --> 00:03:24.850
But they used to have things
called phones and phone books

00:03:24.850 --> 00:03:26.420
that were tethered
to the wall.

00:03:26.420 --> 00:03:29.300
And this is where you would
look for information about

00:03:29.300 --> 00:03:31.870
people who list themselves as
providing psychotherapy.

00:03:31.870 --> 00:03:33.980
All you have to do is put your
name in that listing, even

00:03:33.980 --> 00:03:35.840
easier on the internet maybe.

00:03:35.840 --> 00:03:37.560
A psychiatrist, the big
difference between

00:03:37.560 --> 00:03:41.110
psychiatrist in one practical
sense and psychologist is

00:03:41.110 --> 00:03:43.440
psychiatrist of course,
go to medical school.

00:03:43.440 --> 00:03:45.350
And they have prescription
privileges.

00:03:45.350 --> 00:03:47.290
They can write prescriptions
for drugs.

00:03:47.290 --> 00:03:52.260
That's rare to nonexistent
currently among psychologists.

00:03:52.260 --> 00:03:55.800
Psychoanalyst, here's Sigmund
Freud in the original

00:03:55.800 --> 00:03:58.120
psychotherapy couch.

00:03:58.120 --> 00:04:01.610
And I think we've barely
mentioned Freud so far in this

00:04:01.610 --> 00:04:02.690
course, right?

00:04:02.690 --> 00:04:05.530
Which is kind of a big
shock to many people.

00:04:05.530 --> 00:04:07.200
You might have thought coming
into this course that there'd

00:04:07.200 --> 00:04:09.870
be Freud, Freud, Freud.

00:04:09.870 --> 00:04:11.880
And you know, that we would be
sitting there and that we'd be

00:04:11.880 --> 00:04:13.670
discussing ideas about
Freudian theory.

00:04:13.670 --> 00:04:15.630
I'll come back to that
in a moment.

00:04:15.630 --> 00:04:18.560
Clinical psychologists can
provide psychotherapy.

00:04:18.560 --> 00:04:21.269
Counseling psychologists in
schools, clinical social

00:04:21.269 --> 00:04:26.970
workers, clergy, peer groups,
self-help books.

00:04:26.970 --> 00:04:29.540
So let me just return to Freud
just for a moment.

00:04:29.540 --> 00:04:32.070
Because intellectually, I think
most people will agree

00:04:32.070 --> 00:04:35.100
that Freud was a giant mind.

00:04:35.100 --> 00:04:38.740
And that in many ways, the
complexity of the modern human

00:04:38.740 --> 00:04:42.630
mind, the idea that we're made
up of different parts,

00:04:42.630 --> 00:04:45.580
different feelings, that we're
not just one simple operation

00:04:45.580 --> 00:04:49.050
machine, but that we have
conflicts, different feelings,

00:04:49.050 --> 00:04:51.560
and thoughts, and patterns
all within us.

00:04:51.560 --> 00:04:54.650
Freud probably articulated that
thought more powerfully

00:04:54.650 --> 00:04:56.910
than anybody else in many ways,
as a modern way in which

00:04:56.910 --> 00:04:58.020
we view people, right.

00:04:58.020 --> 00:04:59.330
People are not just
simple things.

00:04:59.330 --> 00:05:01.840
They're complicated things, full
of tensions and desires.

00:05:01.840 --> 00:05:03.420
They're all mixed together.

00:05:03.420 --> 00:05:07.720
At the same time, the specific
ideas that Freud articulated

00:05:07.720 --> 00:05:10.480
using psychodynamic theories
like free association,

00:05:10.480 --> 00:05:13.250
resistance, transference,
interpretation, trying to have

00:05:13.250 --> 00:05:16.250
a corrective emotional
experience, where you go back

00:05:16.250 --> 00:05:18.360
to your youth and
you figure out

00:05:18.360 --> 00:05:19.360
something bad that happened.

00:05:19.360 --> 00:05:22.250
And if you can somehow grapple
with that, that will let you

00:05:22.250 --> 00:05:28.030
be free of the consequences
of that early experience.

00:05:28.030 --> 00:05:30.740
Almost none of that has
withstood the scrutiny of

00:05:30.740 --> 00:05:31.550
practical science.

00:05:31.550 --> 00:05:33.180
A lot of it, you don't
even know how you

00:05:33.180 --> 00:05:34.910
could begin to test.

00:05:34.910 --> 00:05:38.050
Now for those of you who become
physicians, and the

00:05:38.050 --> 00:05:40.790
rest of you will be patients,
it's amazing how much of

00:05:40.790 --> 00:05:42.690
medicine is not science-based.

00:05:42.690 --> 00:05:44.510
It's amazing.

00:05:44.510 --> 00:05:47.940
So you hear the cry all the time
in medicine, we need to

00:05:47.940 --> 00:05:50.920
have science, or evidence-based
medicine.

00:05:50.920 --> 00:05:52.090
And you might have thought,
well, what

00:05:52.090 --> 00:05:53.000
else are they doing?

00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:53.380
OK.

00:05:53.380 --> 00:05:55.570
And the answer is they're
treated as best they can and

00:05:55.570 --> 00:05:56.420
what works, works.

00:05:56.420 --> 00:05:58.150
A lot of stuff they don't
understand exactly when and

00:05:58.150 --> 00:05:58.900
why it works.

00:05:58.900 --> 00:06:00.520
But they apply what they can.

00:06:00.520 --> 00:06:03.310
There's a patient in distress.

00:06:03.310 --> 00:06:08.170
Freudian ideas are everything
that you know about ids, and

00:06:08.170 --> 00:06:10.530
electric complexes, and all
that kinds of stuff.

00:06:10.530 --> 00:06:14.620
Hard to prove that they exist
in any scientific sense.

00:06:14.620 --> 00:06:17.830
So weirdly, Freud is in many
ways marginalized in the

00:06:17.830 --> 00:06:20.820
current scientific psychology.

00:06:20.820 --> 00:06:23.030
That doesn't mean he wasn't a
creative mind that influenced

00:06:23.030 --> 00:06:26.200
the way people think about the
human mind, and treating the

00:06:26.200 --> 00:06:27.380
human mind.

00:06:27.380 --> 00:06:31.060
But the specific ideas he has
are in many ways at the edge

00:06:31.060 --> 00:06:33.350
of the field.

00:06:33.350 --> 00:06:38.060
So more central to the field
is work called cognitive

00:06:38.060 --> 00:06:39.470
behavioral therapy, or CBT.

00:06:39.470 --> 00:06:41.330
This is Aaron Beck,
who's maybe the

00:06:41.330 --> 00:06:42.960
foremost figure in that.

00:06:42.960 --> 00:06:46.450
And that CBT was developed to
be exactly the opposite in

00:06:46.450 --> 00:06:48.420
many senses of psychoanalysis.

00:06:48.420 --> 00:06:51.170
So similar because it's about
behavior, and about the

00:06:51.170 --> 00:06:54.310
interaction between a clinician
and a person seeking

00:06:54.310 --> 00:06:57.380
a sort of happier, healthier
approach to things.

00:06:57.380 --> 00:07:01.290
But the Woody Allen version of
psychotherapy, where you go

00:07:01.290 --> 00:07:05.530
for 40 years weekly to your
psychiatrist on the west side

00:07:05.530 --> 00:07:07.200
and talk through your
problems, OK.

00:07:07.200 --> 00:07:10.880
That idea, people said, well,
that's fine if you do that.

00:07:10.880 --> 00:07:12.780
But is that really what we mean
by treating somebody?

00:07:12.780 --> 00:07:17.130
So Beck said, in things like
anxiety or depression, people

00:07:17.130 --> 00:07:20.080
have dysfunctional beliefs that
the world is threatening,

00:07:20.080 --> 00:07:22.720
that the world is hopeless.

00:07:22.720 --> 00:07:25.210
These are sort of logical
thinking errors that you can

00:07:25.210 --> 00:07:27.710
work yourself out of to make
yourself less depressed or

00:07:27.710 --> 00:07:29.010
less anxious.

00:07:29.010 --> 00:07:31.790
That you should focus not on
childhood causes of what

00:07:31.790 --> 00:07:34.250
happened, but on current
problems you face day-to-day

00:07:34.250 --> 00:07:35.610
and how to grapple with them.

00:07:35.610 --> 00:07:39.190
Develop strategies that don't
make you get down and

00:07:39.190 --> 00:07:41.510
depressed, or fearful
and anxious.

00:07:41.510 --> 00:07:43.220
And that it should
be time limited.

00:07:43.220 --> 00:07:45.720
Eight weeks or something, from
beginning to end period, not

00:07:45.720 --> 00:07:49.900
an endless review of your life
and roots of your life.

00:07:49.900 --> 00:07:52.960
And so people are like that
because of part, it's easy to

00:07:52.960 --> 00:07:54.630
test in research studies.

00:07:54.630 --> 00:07:56.980
It's been shown to be pretty
effective, pretty much on a

00:07:56.980 --> 00:07:59.220
par with medications
in most studies.

00:07:59.220 --> 00:08:01.910
And in some cases, better.

00:08:01.910 --> 00:08:04.350
And a psychoanalysis
could go forever.

00:08:04.350 --> 00:08:07.490
It's hard to experimentally
test that in many ways.

00:08:07.490 --> 00:08:10.170
So there was questions about
whether psychotherapy works.

00:08:10.170 --> 00:08:12.480
And if you're kind of a
scientist, you kind of like

00:08:12.480 --> 00:08:15.080
biological stuff like pills,
not talking, right.

00:08:15.080 --> 00:08:18.040
Although talk is
very powerful.

00:08:18.040 --> 00:08:20.230
And now, and early on,
people say, well,

00:08:20.230 --> 00:08:22.190
maybe it's all baloney.

00:08:22.190 --> 00:08:25.350
And I would say that starting
around 1980 from this review,

00:08:25.350 --> 00:08:27.130
people said, no, there's
a lot to it.

00:08:27.130 --> 00:08:29.040
Although not everything
we wish it did.

00:08:29.040 --> 00:08:30.610
So they performed
a meta-analysis.

00:08:30.610 --> 00:08:32.130
You may have heard of these
kinds of things.

00:08:32.130 --> 00:08:34.659
Where it was a quantitative
method for averaging results

00:08:34.659 --> 00:08:36.159
of a large number of
different studies.

00:08:36.159 --> 00:08:37.890
The ideas is that statistically,
if you combined

00:08:37.890 --> 00:08:40.039
many different studies, you
might have a sort of an

00:08:40.039 --> 00:08:40.890
overall picture.

00:08:40.890 --> 00:08:43.100
It's not just describing them,
but taking their actual

00:08:43.100 --> 00:08:44.820
statistics and combining them.

00:08:44.820 --> 00:08:47.440
Looking for the effect size,
something about the consistent

00:08:47.440 --> 00:08:51.040
size of, in this case, a
psychotherapy treatment.

00:08:51.040 --> 00:08:53.000
And then asking what happens
in the terms

00:08:53.000 --> 00:08:54.290
of the effect size.

00:08:54.290 --> 00:08:55.430
And you come out with a picture

00:08:55.430 --> 00:08:56.840
like this in the study.

00:08:56.840 --> 00:08:59.720
That you have an average effect
side of a 0.7 that is

00:08:59.720 --> 00:09:00.310
treated people.

00:09:00.310 --> 00:09:01.870
This is getting better
this way.

00:09:01.870 --> 00:09:04.610
We're on average better across
many different studies.

00:09:04.610 --> 00:09:06.270
So the treatment seemed
to move people

00:09:06.270 --> 00:09:08.310
in the right direction.

00:09:08.310 --> 00:09:13.730
And that furthermore, about half
receiving psychotherapy,

00:09:13.730 --> 00:09:16.730
the average person was better
off than 80% of the people who

00:09:16.730 --> 00:09:17.370
didn't get it.

00:09:17.370 --> 00:09:18.940
So not everybody benefits
greatly.

00:09:18.940 --> 00:09:20.680
But many people benefit some.

00:09:20.680 --> 00:09:22.740
About 10% got worse.

00:09:22.740 --> 00:09:26.076
So this number says only
a few get worse.

00:09:26.076 --> 00:09:29.120
A weirdly different thing, was
that people have always want

00:09:29.120 --> 00:09:32.590
to develop very clear ideas
about which forms, of many

00:09:32.590 --> 00:09:35.360
possible forms of behavioral
therapy are really powerful

00:09:35.360 --> 00:09:37.630
for which difficulty, or
which kind of person.

00:09:37.630 --> 00:09:38.790
It makes sense, right?

00:09:38.790 --> 00:09:40.580
That the different problem
you're facing and the kind of

00:09:40.580 --> 00:09:43.760
person you are, a different
kind of talk therapy,

00:09:43.760 --> 00:09:46.420
different kind of CBT would
be powerful for you.

00:09:46.420 --> 00:09:48.020
And that's been incredibly
hard to

00:09:48.020 --> 00:09:49.310
demonstrate in most cases.

00:09:49.310 --> 00:09:51.330
Shockingly hard to
demonstrate.

00:09:51.330 --> 00:09:54.680
And part of that comes from
these kinds of studies.

00:09:54.680 --> 00:09:57.610
So the best of these kinds
of studies have random

00:09:57.610 --> 00:10:00.780
assignments and to different
kinds of treatment.

00:10:00.780 --> 00:10:03.010
For psychotherapy, you might
have a wait list.

00:10:03.010 --> 00:10:05.930
And you could be blinded as to
getting a good or bad version.

00:10:05.930 --> 00:10:07.450
So again, here's another
meta-analysis.

00:10:07.450 --> 00:10:09.900
And here's the kind
of big surprise.

00:10:09.900 --> 00:10:12.450
Again in this next
meta-analysis, about 2:1

00:10:12.450 --> 00:10:14.820
chance of improving, versus
control, if you sit there and

00:10:14.820 --> 00:10:15.460
don't do anything.

00:10:15.460 --> 00:10:18.560
So that's again, a good way to
go if you're in distress.

00:10:18.560 --> 00:10:21.610
Here's kind of a surprise,
credentials don't matter,

00:10:21.610 --> 00:10:26.000
Ph.D., M.D., no degree.

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:27.970
There might be something about
the kind of person who's a

00:10:27.970 --> 00:10:30.610
more or less effective
therapists.

00:10:30.610 --> 00:10:33.230
That's been hard to
scientifically demonstrate.

00:10:33.230 --> 00:10:35.570
The degree you have has never
correlated with the

00:10:35.570 --> 00:10:37.210
effectiveness of
the treatment.

00:10:37.210 --> 00:10:39.110
Here's another big surprise,
the experience of the

00:10:39.110 --> 00:10:40.450
therapist didn't matter.

00:10:40.450 --> 00:10:43.700
Beginning, middle, end of
career, seen a lot of

00:10:43.700 --> 00:10:45.400
patients, not seen a lot of
patients, that doesn't

00:10:45.400 --> 00:10:46.620
consistently matter.

00:10:46.620 --> 00:10:48.970
The type of therapy doesn't
consistently matter.

00:10:48.970 --> 00:10:53.220
The length of therapy doesn't
matter in any way that people

00:10:53.220 --> 00:10:54.910
have been able to show
scientifically.

00:10:54.910 --> 00:10:58.660
What seems to matter is talking
to somebody who

00:10:58.660 --> 00:11:01.560
listens to you on a
consistent basis.

00:11:01.560 --> 00:11:01.870
Yeah?

00:11:01.870 --> 00:11:04.702
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:11:04.702 --> 00:11:06.280
PROFESSOR JOHN GABRIELI: That's
for all these kinds of

00:11:06.280 --> 00:11:06.940
things, right.

00:11:06.940 --> 00:11:09.810
So on the one hand, you wouldn't
want to push it to an

00:11:09.810 --> 00:11:11.610
absurdest thing because there
are humans involved.

00:11:11.610 --> 00:11:13.130
You wouldn't want to say, well,
just for fun, let's take

00:11:13.130 --> 00:11:16.180
somebody's who like a
three-year-old and send them

00:11:16.180 --> 00:11:17.480
out to see what they
can do, right.

00:11:17.480 --> 00:11:19.400
So I mean, there's a real
person involved

00:11:19.400 --> 00:11:20.650
here in real distress.

00:11:20.650 --> 00:11:22.010
But whenever they've
done these kinds of

00:11:22.010 --> 00:11:22.950
things, they adjusted--

00:11:22.950 --> 00:11:26.600
And CBT is the most consistently
studied because

00:11:26.600 --> 00:11:27.960
it's very organized.

00:11:27.960 --> 00:11:30.080
Psychotherapy, so many people
do so differently.

00:11:30.080 --> 00:11:33.120
It's very hard to study.

00:11:33.120 --> 00:11:34.760
And CBT is time-limited.

00:11:34.760 --> 00:11:38.560
So that approach seems more
