Now what I wanted to give you
a feeling if you think about

00:18:23.170 --> 00:18:26.230
this, you know you are the
doctor talking to somebody.

00:18:26.230 --> 00:18:28.510
And you know, disturbed sleep,
but how disturbed

00:18:28.510 --> 00:18:29.260
does it have to be?

00:18:29.260 --> 00:18:31.770
Diminished appetite, but
how diminish, right?

00:18:31.770 --> 00:18:32.590
Loss of energy?

00:18:32.590 --> 00:18:34.850
Well, we all have periods where
we're more sluggish or

00:18:34.850 --> 00:18:36.640
more focused, right?

00:18:36.640 --> 00:18:39.590
I mean so usually depression,
these things are so extreme.

00:18:39.590 --> 00:18:40.540
It's very obvious.

00:18:40.540 --> 00:18:42.070
Sometimes it's at the edge.

00:18:42.070 --> 00:18:44.090
And there's a range
of these things.

00:18:44.090 --> 00:18:45.830
We know there's a genetic
predisposition.

00:18:45.830 --> 00:18:49.950
If you have identical twins
50%, dizygotic 10%.

00:18:49.950 --> 00:18:51.610
But we know there's
environmental factors.

00:18:51.610 --> 00:18:55.820
So it's very hard to figure
out whether diseases are

00:18:55.820 --> 00:18:58.700
getting more or less
common over time.

00:18:58.700 --> 00:19:00.760
Because especially in
psychiatric diseases, the

00:19:00.760 --> 00:19:04.350
criteria that defines those
diseased change over time.

00:19:04.350 --> 00:19:06.725
So you don't know which it
is, sensitivity to it.

00:19:06.725 --> 00:19:08.420
You know, 30 years ago teachers

00:19:08.420 --> 00:19:10.320
never heard of autism.

00:19:10.320 --> 00:19:13.850
Now every teacher in
kindergarten is watching out

00:19:13.850 --> 00:19:14.900
for autism.

00:19:14.900 --> 00:19:17.470
So it's spotted much more
quickly and consistently.

00:19:17.470 --> 00:19:19.250
So people say it's going up.

00:19:19.250 --> 00:19:20.280
Is it really going up?

00:19:20.280 --> 00:19:22.230
Is it being detected
more often?

00:19:22.230 --> 00:19:24.680
It's very hard to tell
those things apart.

00:19:24.680 --> 00:19:27.180
But where evidence is available,
since 1940 there's

00:19:27.180 --> 00:19:29.980
nearly a 10-year drop in the
average age of the first

00:19:29.980 --> 00:19:32.030
instance of depression.

00:19:32.030 --> 00:19:35.550
So is this 10-year drop that
