Who are these girls who have
a high risk for getting

00:23:26.280 --> 00:23:29.090
depression?

00:23:29.090 --> 00:23:30.450
What does high mean?

00:23:30.450 --> 00:23:32.820
Sorry to put you on the spot.

00:23:32.820 --> 00:23:34.150
What does high mean?

00:23:34.150 --> 00:23:36.370
They're in a family where they
have a parent with depression.

00:23:36.370 --> 00:23:37.010
OK.

00:23:37.010 --> 00:23:39.890
So you can't tell that maybe
having a parent with

00:23:39.890 --> 00:23:42.430
depression ups the child's
focus on the negative.

00:23:42.430 --> 00:23:44.400
Because they've had some
difficult things to deal with

00:23:44.400 --> 00:23:45.570
in their family.

00:23:45.570 --> 00:23:48.320
Maybe they have genes that draw
them to negative things,

00:23:48.320 --> 00:23:49.210
or maybe both.

00:23:49.210 --> 00:23:50.930
You can't tell that apart from
these kinds of studies.

00:23:54.440 --> 00:23:59.190
Every once in while there's
sort of a success story in

00:23:59.190 --> 00:24:00.140
brain sciences.

00:24:00.140 --> 00:24:03.380
And why it's terribly important
is this, to this

00:24:03.380 --> 00:24:06.300
day, as one of the speaker said,
there's people who think

00:24:06.300 --> 00:24:08.455
psychiatric disorders are
just for sissies.

00:24:08.455 --> 00:24:10.090
That you just stop
being depressed.

00:24:10.090 --> 00:24:11.940
Just don't listen to those
voices, right.

00:24:11.940 --> 00:24:13.730
Just stop washing your hands.

00:24:13.730 --> 00:24:17.570
And what's very confusing about
this message is for

00:24:17.570 --> 00:24:20.760
people for example, who are
addicted to substances or have

00:24:20.760 --> 00:24:24.420
alcoholism, we ask them to stop
drinking and stop taking

00:24:24.420 --> 00:24:25.900
drugs, with support.

00:24:25.900 --> 00:24:27.905
But we say it's, we think
it's somewhere in

00:24:27.905 --> 00:24:29.260
you to stop, right.

00:24:29.260 --> 00:24:31.810
So with the right support,
we think it's

00:24:31.810 --> 00:24:33.280
somewhere in you to stop.

00:24:33.280 --> 00:24:34.095
So it's kind of hard.

00:24:34.095 --> 00:24:35.180
Where is that line, right?

00:24:35.180 --> 00:24:38.900
CBT is getting people to find
ways to think so they're not

00:24:38.900 --> 00:24:40.080
anxious or not depressed.

00:24:40.080 --> 00:24:41.490
Again, we think it's
in them with the

00:24:41.490 --> 00:24:42.460
right kind of support.

00:24:42.460 --> 00:24:44.810
So on the one hand we ask
people to get themselves

00:24:44.810 --> 00:24:46.520
healthier with support, right.

00:24:46.520 --> 00:24:47.540
So it's kind of tricky.

00:24:47.540 --> 00:24:49.410
Where is the line of
responsibility?

00:24:49.410 --> 00:24:51.710
But I think one of the triumphs
of modern brain

00:24:51.710 --> 00:24:55.210
imaging is to make visible the
brain basis of psychiatric

00:24:55.210 --> 00:24:57.520
disorders on average.

00:24:57.520 --> 00:25:00.675
So because there's no broken
arm, no broken leg, no tumor

00:25:00.675 --> 00:25:02.730
or anything like that, right.

00:25:02.730 --> 00:25:05.110
That promotes discussion,
or consideration, is our

00:25:05.110 --> 00:25:08.500
psychiatric disorders real
brain differences?

00:25:08.500 --> 00:25:10.830
And I can also tell you that
unfortunately, we're not

00:25:10.830 --> 00:25:14.860
anywhere near where a house
can put up a picture of

00:25:14.860 --> 00:25:17.730
somebody's brain and say, oh,
this person's certainly has

00:25:17.730 --> 00:25:21.870
depression, or schizophrenia,
or ADHD, or dyslexia, or any

00:25:21.870 --> 00:25:23.480
difficulty that you know of.

00:25:23.480 --> 00:25:26.110
Nobody can say that on the basis
of a single brain scan

00:25:26.110 --> 00:25:27.150
for a single person.

00:25:27.150 --> 00:25:27.750
We want to.

00:25:27.750 --> 00:25:29.120
We're not there yet.

00:25:29.120 --> 00:25:31.570
But we can see on average
differences between people who

00:25:31.570 --> 00:25:34.010
have a diagnosis and
people who don't.

00:25:34.010 --> 00:25:36.380
So here's a PET, positron
emission tomography, top of

00:25:36.380 --> 00:25:37.960
the brain, bottom
of the brain.

00:25:37.960 --> 00:25:41.790
They found less activation in
this so called subgenual

00:25:41.790 --> 00:25:42.650
anterior cingulate.

00:25:42.650 --> 00:25:45.110
The anterior cingulate is this
cortex that sits over the

00:25:45.110 --> 00:25:46.450
corpus callosum.

00:25:46.450 --> 00:25:49.540
And here in this bottom part
of the anterior cingulate,

00:25:49.540 --> 00:25:53.180
less activation in patients
with depression

00:25:53.180 --> 00:25:54.590
than control subjects.

00:25:54.590 --> 00:25:58.870
And then, looking at structure
now, physical volume.

00:25:58.870 --> 00:26:03.100
Also reduced volume in these
areas, in patients with both

00:26:03.100 --> 00:26:05.540
unipolar and bipolar, in
this case, depression.

00:26:05.540 --> 00:26:07.050
So now we have both
a structural

00:26:07.050 --> 00:26:08.340
difference on average.

00:26:08.340 --> 00:26:11.740
And a functional difference
on average.

00:26:11.740 --> 00:26:14.160
Sometimes in psychiatry there'd
be a brain banks.

00:26:14.160 --> 00:26:15.990
When patients passed
away, they'd donate

00:26:15.990 --> 00:26:17.700
their brains to research.

00:26:17.700 --> 00:26:20.175
And people said, let's go look
in this area in people who

00:26:20.175 --> 00:26:23.060
have passed away so we can look
at the cellular level of

00:26:23.060 --> 00:26:23.800
what's going on there.

00:26:23.800 --> 00:26:25.160
We can't see with brain imaging

00:26:25.160 --> 00:26:27.440
anything close to cells.

00:26:27.440 --> 00:26:29.270
But with post-mortem
analysis we can.

00:26:29.270 --> 00:26:30.440
And there was a big surprise.

00:26:30.440 --> 00:26:33.870
The big surprise was when they
looked in this region, there

00:26:33.870 --> 00:26:37.720
was a reduced number of cells,
which goes with the reduced

00:26:37.720 --> 00:26:40.050
the volume, and the reduced
activation.

00:26:40.050 --> 00:26:42.310
But it was in the neurons,
it was the glial.

00:26:42.310 --> 00:26:44.280
And you go glial?

00:26:44.280 --> 00:26:45.840
We haven't talked about
glial for a long time.

00:26:45.840 --> 00:26:48.200
You know neurons are the stuff
that compute the mind.

00:26:48.200 --> 00:26:49.260
We all agree with that.

00:26:49.260 --> 00:26:51.320
Glial are essential for
brain function.

00:26:51.320 --> 00:26:53.050
So we don't understand
what that means.

00:26:53.050 --> 00:26:55.350
That these patients would have
an equal number of neurons but

00:26:55.350 --> 00:26:56.660
a reduced number of glial.

00:26:56.660 --> 00:26:58.240
We just don't know
what that means.

00:26:58.240 --> 00:26:59.340
But it was a big surprise.

00:26:59.340 --> 00:27:03.710
And over time I think maybe
we'll think about that.

00:27:03.710 --> 00:27:05.840
And furthermore, imaging
studies looking at the

00:27:05.840 --> 00:27:08.300
anterior cingulate found that
if you looked at the

00:27:08.300 --> 00:27:10.340
pre-treatment activity in
this brain region--

00:27:10.340 --> 00:27:12.440
I'll show another example
in a moment--

00:27:12.440 --> 00:27:16.410
you could see not only changes
that occur with treatment, but

00:27:16.410 --> 00:27:19.540
that differences predicted which
patients would benefit

00:27:19.540 --> 00:27:20.710
more or less for treatment.

00:27:20.710 --> 00:27:23.480
So all these conversion areas
about the importance of the

00:27:23.480 --> 00:27:27.840
anterior cingulate cortex in
depression although nobody

00:27:27.840 --> 00:27:29.730
thinks that's the whole story.

00:27:29.730 --> 00:27:32.230
That the anterior cingulate is
part of a network of areas

00:27:32.230 --> 00:27:36.190
that are compromised
in depression.

00:27:36.190 --> 00:27:38.720
And another thing that I think
is sort of an exciting

00:27:38.720 --> 00:27:42.210
direction is each dot here
is an individual person.

00:27:42.210 --> 00:27:44.380
Here's how much they improved.

00:27:44.380 --> 00:27:45.810
Better is down here.

00:27:45.810 --> 00:27:47.270
This is the patients who
improved the most with

00:27:47.270 --> 00:27:50.270
treatment, the least
with CBT treatment.

00:27:50.270 --> 00:27:51.850
And this is the initial
activation.

00:27:51.850 --> 00:27:54.560
So it's telling you maybe that
these are the patients who

00:27:54.560 --> 00:27:56.490
really should get CBT.

00:27:56.490 --> 00:27:57.910
And maybe these are
the patients who

00:27:57.910 --> 00:27:59.390
didn't respond so much.

00:27:59.390 --> 00:28:01.910
And maybe they should get, by
the initial brain measure,

00:28:01.910 --> 00:28:03.440
some other form of treatment.

00:28:03.440 --> 00:28:06.340
So that's I think an exciting
areas where we could develop

00:28:06.340 --> 00:28:08.950
enough understanding of
diversity among patients to

00:28:08.950 --> 00:28:11.370
understand which patient might
benefit for which treatment.

00:28:11.370 --> 00:28:13.050
But we're just at
the beginning of

00:28:13.050 --> 00:28:15.580
that kind of knowledge.

00:28:15.580 --> 00:28:19.180
So what about treatments
for depression?

00:28:19.180 --> 00:28:21.230
In 2005, that's some years ago
now, but there's an estimated

00:28:21.230 --> 00:28:23.110
27 million people in the US.

00:28:23.110 --> 00:28:26.270
There's $10billion now
and more in sales.

00:28:26.270 --> 00:28:29.380
That's to drugs or CBT forms
of treatment of depression,

00:28:29.380 --> 00:28:32.360
the most common forms
of treatment.

00:28:32.360 --> 00:28:33.770
Even with these treatments--

00:28:33.770 --> 00:28:34.770
so here's the message.

00:28:34.770 --> 00:28:37.220
Everybody agrees I think and
reasonably, that if you know

00:28:37.220 --> 00:28:39.570
somebody with depression, or
you're depressed yourself, or

00:28:39.570 --> 00:28:41.800
anxiety, but we're talking about
depression, getting help

00:28:41.800 --> 00:28:42.540
is a good idea.

00:28:42.540 --> 00:28:44.380
Many people get helped.

00:28:44.380 --> 00:28:47.100
But the help is not nearly
what we wish

00:28:47.100 --> 00:28:48.150
it were in the field.

00:28:48.150 --> 00:28:50.590
So in depression, about
half of patients

00:28:50.590 --> 00:28:52.270
don't achieve remission.

00:28:52.270 --> 00:28:55.790
They still are depressed
even after medicine

00:28:55.790 --> 00:28:57.490
or behavioral treatment.

00:28:57.490 --> 00:28:59.720
And even among those who improve
a lot, there's still

00:28:59.720 --> 00:29:00.820
residual symptoms.

00:29:00.820 --> 00:29:03.770
It's not as if patients
typically or often escape

00:29:03.770 --> 00:29:04.870
entirely that.

00:29:04.870 --> 00:29:06.970
But they can improve a lot.

00:29:06.970 --> 00:29:09.130
But the other thing is since
nobody knows which approach to

00:29:09.130 --> 00:29:12.110
take with which patient by any
scientific evidence, it's all

00:29:12.110 --> 00:29:12.900
trial and error.

00:29:12.900 --> 00:29:15.310
So finding a good
treatment for a

00:29:15.310 --> 00:29:16.630
person could take months.

00:29:16.630 --> 00:29:18.810
And by then some people just
give up and don't come back.

00:29:18.810 --> 00:29:20.810
Because in the throes of the
diseases, or they just figure

00:29:20.810 --> 00:29:22.020
they're not going
to be helped.

00:29:22.020 --> 00:29:23.400
It's all hit and miss.

00:29:23.400 --> 00:29:25.760
I have a colleague in CSAIL
the computer science

00:29:25.760 --> 00:29:26.660
department.

00:29:26.660 --> 00:29:28.180
And we're doing research
with her.

00:29:28.180 --> 00:29:31.230
And we say, you know, if you
go to a doctor now with

00:29:31.230 --> 00:29:35.140
depression, or anxiety, or
social anxiety disorder, it's

00:29:35.140 --> 00:29:37.600
almost completely random whether
they assign you to one

00:29:37.600 --> 00:29:40.900
treatment or another within
some broad constraints.

00:29:40.900 --> 00:29:43.830
There's no scientific basis
for knowing what drug you

00:29:43.830 --> 00:29:46.920
should get, or a drug plus
CBT, or CBT only.

00:29:46.920 --> 00:29:48.170
It's completely random.

00:29:48.170 --> 00:29:50.660
It's depending on the
physician's background and

00:29:50.660 --> 00:29:51.660
intuitions.

00:29:51.660 --> 00:29:53.600
There's no scientific basis
for knowing that.

00:29:53.600 --> 00:29:56.510
So there's a lot to
be discovered.

00:29:56.510 --> 00:29:58.720
So sometimes people are trying
to say, well, let's compare

00:29:58.720 --> 00:30:03.180
placebo treatments to a
medicine treatment, to

00:30:03.180 --> 00:30:04.850
cognitive behavioral therapy.

00:30:04.850 --> 00:30:07.390
Here's responding to treatment,
improving.

00:30:07.390 --> 00:30:09.850
So better than placebo
or both drugs, about

00:30:09.850 --> 00:30:12.530
eight weeks, and CBT.

00:30:12.530 --> 00:30:14.810
And then at 16 weeks there's
even more of a gain.

00:30:14.810 --> 00:30:19.140
And they look very similar on
average across patients.

00:30:19.140 --> 00:30:21.860
And if you look over time now,
after the treatment is over,

00:30:21.860 --> 00:30:24.750
at how many people sort of what
the long-term picture is

00:30:24.750 --> 00:30:26.260
because you care about that.

00:30:26.260 --> 00:30:28.850
I mean there's two things,
getting people out of crises

00:30:28.850 --> 00:30:31.090
and then keeping your
head above water.

00:30:31.090 --> 00:30:33.770
It seems like the group that
maintains the best response

00:30:33.770 --> 00:30:37.500
are the people who had the
CBT over longer periods.

00:30:37.500 --> 00:30:38.560
So you might say, well
why don't we just

00:30:38.560 --> 00:30:40.120
give everybody CBT?

00:30:40.120 --> 00:30:42.050
And part of it is not everybody
responds to that.

00:30:42.050 --> 00:30:44.530
Some patients for example, with
severe depression are

00:30:44.530 --> 00:30:45.830
talking about suicide.

00:30:45.830 --> 00:30:48.840
You don't feel like you can wait
8 weeks or 16 weeks to

00:30:48.840 --> 00:30:50.760
let a CBT process happen.

00:30:50.760 --> 00:30:54.340
Some patients just don't have
the energy to go to sessions

00:30:54.340 --> 00:30:55.500
and work on things.

00:30:55.500 --> 00:30:57.460
And you need to rescue
them from that.

00:30:57.460 --> 00:31:01.000
So there's all kinds of issues
about what kinds of treatment

00:31:01.000 --> 00:31:03.215
ultimately are practical and
effective for patients.

00:31:05.870 --> 00:31:10.120
So in clinical trials when
they try a drug.

00:31:10.120 --> 00:31:12.090
And I'll focus on drugs
for the moment.

00:31:12.090 --> 00:31:13.520
There's a random assignment.

00:31:13.520 --> 00:31:15.870
Patients with the diagnosis are
assigned either to or a

00:31:15.870 --> 00:31:17.870
placebo or a drug.

00:31:17.870 --> 00:31:20.580
The physicians are not supposed
to know what it is.

00:31:20.580 --> 00:31:23.580
Response means just getting
better, which is valuable.

00:31:23.580 --> 00:31:26.800
Remission means, that you don't
qualify for having the

00:31:26.800 --> 00:31:28.440
disease anymore.

00:31:28.440 --> 00:31:31.410
How people decide whether
you have depression?

00:31:31.410 --> 00:31:32.400
They take a full history.

00:31:32.400 --> 00:31:35.220
But they'll often use some
sort of rating scale.

00:31:35.220 --> 00:31:37.550
One of the most common is a
Hamilton to say how severely

00:31:37.550 --> 00:31:38.680
depressed are you.

00:31:38.680 --> 00:31:40.750
So they can document
it at beginning.

00:31:40.750 --> 00:31:42.120
Then give that to
you at the end.

00:31:42.120 --> 00:31:44.470
And see how severely depressed
at the end.

00:31:44.470 --> 00:31:46.880
So one thing to know that's
really interesting, and really

00:31:46.880 --> 00:31:49.880
a problem from the field is
there's incredibly strong

00:31:49.880 --> 00:31:51.060
placebo responses.

00:31:51.060 --> 00:31:56.920
In many studies the placebo
responses rival the response

00:31:56.920 --> 00:31:58.850
of the drug itself.

00:31:58.850 --> 00:32:01.160
And people have had huge debates
to this day about what

00:32:01.160 --> 00:32:01.630
that means.

00:32:01.630 --> 00:32:02.880
And it's not well understood.

00:32:05.600 --> 00:32:09.120
Some people say nobody is
getting better, that the

00:32:09.120 --> 00:32:11.920
entire thing is regression to
the mean from study entry.

00:32:11.920 --> 00:32:13.810
And what does that mean?

00:32:13.810 --> 00:32:16.570
Well when people have a drug
trials for depression, they

00:32:16.570 --> 00:32:19.490
say we want to treat people with
substantial depression.

00:32:19.490 --> 00:32:21.080
That makes sense, right?

00:32:21.080 --> 00:32:24.130
So you get people who are
substantially depressed.

00:32:24.130 --> 00:32:27.640
Depression is inherently
a fluctuating disorder.

00:32:27.640 --> 00:32:30.360
So from your understanding of
regression to the mean, what

00:32:30.360 --> 00:32:33.280
happens to a patient when you
get them with a really bad

00:32:33.280 --> 00:32:34.530
depression score?

00:32:34.530 --> 00:32:36.560
What's likely to be
there score next

00:32:36.560 --> 00:32:39.010
week, better or worse?

00:32:39.010 --> 00:32:40.800
Better.

00:32:40.800 --> 00:32:43.260
So you get people with really
low depression scores, you

00:32:43.260 --> 00:32:45.150
just sit back, you don't
do anything.

00:32:45.150 --> 00:32:48.980
And because it's a fluctuating
disorder, the chances are that

00:32:48.980 --> 00:32:51.340
because you're getting them at
low points in, they're going

00:32:51.340 --> 00:32:52.320
to get better next week.

00:32:52.320 --> 00:32:52.750
OK.

00:32:52.750 --> 00:32:54.390
That's not a treatment effect.

00:32:54.390 --> 00:32:57.670
That's, you're getting at them
at a low moment by definition.

00:32:57.670 --> 00:33:00.310
So some people say, wow, these
studies could be full of that.

00:33:00.310 --> 00:33:01.900
We say, wow, look at
this drug effect.

00:33:01.900 --> 00:33:02.900
Man, let's push it up.

00:33:02.900 --> 00:33:04.240
Yeah, That's because you're
getting people

00:33:04.240 --> 00:33:05.420
at their worst moment.

00:33:05.420 --> 00:33:07.480
They're going to go back
to their average,

00:33:07.480 --> 00:33:09.380
which will be better.

00:33:09.380 --> 00:33:12.670
Or another really interesting
thing is could our brains have

00:33:12.670 --> 00:33:15.280
incredibly powerful responses
to placebos?

00:33:15.280 --> 00:33:19.930
Do we have in us naturally
occurring healing mechanisms?

00:33:19.930 --> 00:33:22.780
That if we just really
believe in it, than

00:33:22.780 --> 00:33:23.810
those can take over.

00:33:23.810 --> 00:33:24.945
And could we harness that?

00:33:24.945 --> 00:33:27.330
Could we harness these
naturally occurring

00:33:27.330 --> 00:33:30.110
self-healing capacities in
people's minds and brains to

00:33:30.110 --> 00:33:32.960
make themselves better?

00:33:32.960 --> 00:33:36.000
So this is a kind of typical
average results.

00:33:36.000 --> 00:33:37.440
Drug, psychotherapy,
about the same.

00:33:37.440 --> 00:33:39.160
Placebo, pretty close.

00:33:39.160 --> 00:33:41.650
And here's the no
treatment group.

00:33:41.650 --> 00:33:43.950
But even this, kind
of the picture has

00:33:43.950 --> 00:33:45.120
been challenged recently.

00:33:45.120 --> 00:33:48.420
And let me tell you what the
challenges have been and then

00:33:48.420 --> 00:33:50.730
let me tell you what I take
as the takeaway message.

00:33:50.730 --> 00:33:53.540
But it's not scientifically
certain.

00:33:53.540 --> 00:33:56.300
So one person did a
meta-analysis and

00:33:56.300 --> 00:33:57.940
he's totally arguing--

00:33:57.940 --> 00:33:59.700
and let me tell you, the
argument's pretty clever.

00:33:59.700 --> 00:34:02.150
There's no effect of
a drug at all.

00:34:02.150 --> 00:34:05.010
That typically, you get
about 75% of a drug

00:34:05.010 --> 00:34:06.020
effect from the placebo.

00:34:06.020 --> 00:34:06.620
That's huge.

